<i><font size =-3>And I will strike down upon thee with great vengeance and furious anger those who attempt to poison and destroy my brothers</font></i></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/udarueivywood.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Darue Ivywood</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 445<br> <font color=#E9D756>(12/19/01 9:30:06 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Hrmm</span><hr size=1> /sigh<br>
<br>
Ok..lemme start off by asking a few questions..<br>
<br>
1) Do you know what a VRM is?<br>
<br>
2) Do you know how much current your CPU draws at no load?<br>
At full load?<br>
<br>
3) Do you know at what rate your current PS can handle those loads?<br>
<br>
and lastly<br>
<br>
4) do you believe all 'blue screen' errors are caused by software?<br>
<br>
Currently, power supplies cannot deliver necessary current*voltage to the CPU fast enough, nor clean enough. Take that in conjunction with Moore's law and you can see a problem that will rear its ugly head in the not so distant future.  As CPU's break the GHz mark( and Im not refering to 1 and 2, but more of 3, 4, and 5+) and software is continually delveloped to push the CPU to the limits (thanks most in part to us gamers, believe it or not but we push the majority of computer technology in connection speeds, CPU stress, and graphics power) there is a need to deliver the right amount of power for the right amount of time at the exact time its needed, to the CPU.<br>
<br>
The CPU is nothing more than billion's of transistors all plugging away at the speed to which it was designed. All these transistors need power(current and voltage ... P=IV .. ohms law for those technologically impaired).  Multiply that by the billions of transistors existing in the CPU (and the billions more to come, once again refering to Moore's Law) there needs to be a way to deliver precision power at the times its most needed. 1st, 2nd and 3rd droop. The VRM's are constantly being upgraded to accomodate for this power hungry beast and so far unable to be done at the rate of which I was talking about.<br>
<br>
In lehmans terms, look at how much more heatsink is on your CPU as compared to the older ones. More transistors = more power = more heat and thermal throttling needs to occur as well (one reason I wont buy AMD over Intel, but thats another discussion alltogether)<br>
<br>
<br>
So, in short, to answer your question its not slower..its faster than is currently available. This is tomorrows technology.<br>
<br>
Why ? you might ask, (and if not, oh well, I needed a coffee break anyway) so lets get it out of the way...<br>
<br>
At these high frequencies (GHz) any kind of glitch, spike, droop, etc.. in power could be construed by the CPU as a data bit. If the CPU reads these occurences as a data bit, any signal integrity is lost and lock-ups usually occur. The blue screen of death. Now, seeing as most home users arent 'that' concerned with this aspect, people who own servers are.( Downed computers = money lost and pissed off customers) VRM's aren't common place in desktop computers but will be found mostly in servers and on dual processor boards (for now..muahahahaha). But as speed increases, power consumption increases as well and a way to manage the power fast and efficiently is needed to maintain the advancement of CPU speeds. <br>
<br>
Simply put, the architecture of today's voltage regulators cannot keep pace with advancment of processors. Processors may experience power droops, causing incorrect data to cause subsequent system crashes or other problems. <br>
As the transistor count goes up then so does the power dissipation. More important, however, is the corresponding increase in frequency, since power increases as the square of the frequency. The only variable that is changeable in the power equation is supply voltage power dissipation which is also proportional to the square of the voltage. So we must reduce voltage as we move forward into the future. The &quot;same-power&quot; voltage for a 0.18micron process is 0.5 volts, compared with 3.3 volts today. But operating at 0.5 volts will present new challenges, since a few millivolts of supply variation or noise across the processor core will now be a significant percentage of transistor switching voltage. <br>
<br>
There needs to be a way to regulate that noise variation at speeds proportional to the CPU. MHz Power is the first step to accomodate tomorrows CPU's.<br>
<br>
Hope that answers your question.<br>
<br>
<br>
 <br>
<br>
<br>
